# Git Workflow Rules

## Branch, Commit, Push, and PR Creation

When creating a new feature or fix:

1. **Create a new branch:**
   ```bash
   git checkout -b fix/description-of-change
   # or
   git checkout -b feature/description-of-feature
   ```

2. **Stage and commit changes:**
   ```bash
   git add <files>
   git commit -m "fix: description of change"
   ```

3. **Push the branch:**
   ```bash
   git push -u origin fix/description-of-change
   ```

4. **Create a PR using curl:**
   ```bash
   curl -X POST \
     -H "Accept: application/vnd.github+json" \
     -H "Authorization: Bearer ${GITHUB_TOKEN}" \
     https://api.github.com/repos/sgedda/mockifyer/pulls \
     -d '{
       "title": "fix: Description of change",
       "body": "## Description\n\nDetailed description of the changes.\n\n## Changes\n\n- Change 1\n- Change 2\n\n## Testing\n\nHow to test the changes.",
       "head": "fix/description-of-change",
       "base": "main"
     }'
   ```

   **Alternative: Use GitHub CLI (simpler):**
   ```bash
   gh pr create --title "fix: Description of change" \
     --body "## Description\n\nDetailed description..." \
     --base main --head fix/description-of-change
   ```

## Commit Message Format

Use conventional commit format:
- `fix:` - Bug fixes
- `feat:` - New features
- `docs:` - Documentation changes
- `refactor:` - Code refactoring
- `test:` - Test changes
- `chore:` - Build/tooling changes

Example: `fix: improve frontend build cache clearing for Contact page deployment`

## PR Description Template

```markdown
## Problem

Description of the issue being solved.

## Solution

How the problem is being solved.

## Changes

- Change 1
- Change 2
- Change 3

## Testing

Steps to verify the changes work correctly.
```
